Quantitative XPS analysis was performed for synthesised composite material to identify the surface elements, including the binding energy peaks. The full scan survey spectrum (Fig. 4
                           ) contains C 1s, N 1s and O 1s binding energy peaks along with the Ti 2p peak, confirming the surface modification of crosslinked hydrogel by TiO2. The high-resolution C 1s spectrum of the functionalized chitosan composite shows five deconvoluted peaks, as shown in Fig. 5a. The peaks positioned at 284.7, 286.3 and 288.1 eV can be assigned to CC, C-O/C-N and O-C=O functionality present in the crosslinked chitosan network [38]. The peaks at 285.6 and 287.3 eV are attributed to the CC and CN moieties of the imidazole rings [33]. Furthermore, the N 1s spectrum is deconvoluted into three major energy peaks (Fig. 5b) at 397.8, 399.7 and 401.2 eV, which are corresponding to CN, CN and –NH groups, respectively in the functionalized chitosan-based nanocomposite [39,40]. The high resolution spectrum of O 1s exhibits four characteristic deconvoluted peaks at 529.6, 530.5, 530.9 and 532.3 eV (Fig. 5c) can be attributed to lattice oxide (O2
                           −), bridging/terminal OH, CO and O-C=O groups, respectively [41]. High resolution XPS spectrum in the region where the binding energy (~455 to 465 eV) of titanium appeared is shown in Fig. 5d. The deconvolution of the Ti 2p spectrum reveals that the spin-orbit splitting photoelectrons (Ti 2p3/2 and Ti 2p1/2) of titanium are found at binding energies of 456.9 and 462.7 eV, respectively. Therefore, the presence of doublets at 456.9 and 462.7 eV with separation of 5.8 eV between the two signals of Ti 2p3/2 and Ti 2p1/2 indicates that titanium is present in the IV oxidation state (Ti4+) [42,43].

In order to investigate the advantages of the hybrid photocatalyst over individually TiO2 and CDs deposited materials, the photocatalytic performance of the different synthesised materials cl-Ch-p(VI), cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs, cl-Ch-p(VI)/CDs and cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs-CDs was studied over 30 min degradation of RB4 and RR15 (Fig. 6
                        ).The results demonstrate that cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs-CDs have the maximum degradative removal ability, while trace degradation of both the dyes occurred using sunlight alone. The efficiency of the synthesised photocatalyst towards degradation of dyes is thus obvious. The crosslinked chitosan alone removed minute quantity of dyes in presence of sunlight, mainly due to the adsorption of the dyes by the copolymer, as a result of electrostatic interactions. By comparison, 53.1% of RB4 and 56.3% of RR15 were degraded by cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs nanocomposite material under sunlight for 30 min. This is explained by both the increase in surface area (Table S1, Supporting Information) as well as the higher absorption of UV light by this composite, compared to pristine chitosan copolymer. However, sunlight consists of only ~3–5% UV light, which is insufficient for complete degradation of the dyes. The degradation of RB4 and RR15 was ~95.8% and ~98.2% complete, respectively, in presence of cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs-CDs nanocomposite material under exposure of sunlight for 30 min, whereas, cl-Ch-p(VI)/CDs degraded ~61.1% and ~65.5% of RB4 and RR15, respectively. Thus, the improvement of the photocatalytic activity of the cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs-CDs nanocomposite can be explained by the incorporation of a visible light active material like CDs, which can absorb photons in the visible range of sunlight to increase the charge separation of electron/hole pair, also increasing the surface area of the material (Table S1, Supporting Information). Furthermore, the photocatalytic degradation of the dye molecules RB4 and RR15 by the cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs-CDs nanocomposite were carried out with variation of time in the presence of sunlight and represented in Fig. S5, Supporting Information. In the presence of sunlight, both dyes degraded faster (k = 0.105 min−1 and 0.133 min−1 for RB4 and RR15, respectively) (Table 1
                        ) in presence of cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs-CDs nanocomposite than that of cl-Ch-p(VI), cl-Ch-p(VI)/TiO2NPs or cl-Ch-p(VI)/CDs.
